article.description:
Shalonda Enis scored 29 points, nine more than her previous career best,
and Allison Feaster added 23 as the Charlotte Sting defeated the
Detroit Shock 92-79.
article.headline: Sting shoot 65 percent from 3-point land
article.linkText: Sting sink 13 treys in rout of Shock
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Shalonda Enis was hoping to break out of a slump Thursday night. She did. And then some. Enis scored 29 points, nine more than her previous career best, and Allison Feaster added 23 as the Charlotte Sting defeated the Detroit Shock 92-79. "That feels really good, especially because I feel like I have been struggling lately," said Enis, who hadn't scored more than 12 points this season. "We are the No. 1 one and No. 2 teams in the East, and I think everyone wants to see who will come up on top. That's why it feels great to win a game like this." The Sting hit a team-record 13 3-pointers, narrowly missing the league record of 14 set by Minnesota in 1999 and tied by Sacramento in 2001. "When we are on, we are a pretty good 3-point-shooting team," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "Ever since Shalonda has been inserted into the starting lineup, she's been a lot better. She did a really good job tonight." Enis was 5-for-5 on 3-pointers while Feaster hit five of nine. "We knew we didn't want to get into a running match with them, so we went to Plan B," Enis said. "We stuck to our plan and we got the result we needed." Charlotte hit 65 percent of its 3-point attempts while Detroit hit just 61.8 percent from the free-throw line. "Give them credit -- they just shot dramatically well tonight," Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "They were hitting deep 3-pointers with us right on them. Those weren't easy shots." Cheryl Ford led Detroit with a career-high 19 points and 12 rebounds, while Swin Cash scored 17 and Kedra Holland-Corn added 14. Deanna Nolan, who will join Ford and Cash as All-Star reserves, had just one point and missed all five shots. "She just didn't show up," Laimbeer said. The Sting won their fifth straight in Detroit. The teams play again on July 10 in Charlotte. "That's a very big game for us," Shock center Ruth Riley said. "They are a playoff contender and so are we, but we need to go down there and get one back from them." Lacey, though, wasn't thinking that far down the road. "Every home game is important, because you have to protect your own floor," she said. "But right now, we are just thinking about Sacramento in a couple days." Charlotte led 54-47 with 14:35 left, before Detroit tied the game at 56. The Sting then went on a 20-5 run to take control. Feaster led the spurt with nine points. Charlotte led 39-37 at the half, thanks to seven 3-pointers. Enis was 3-for-3 and Feaster 2-for-4 on 3s in the half. "Detroit has the best record in the league, so this is a big win," Feaster said. "We had an extraordinary shooting night -- I'm very pleased."

Game notes
Charlotte's Dawn Staley will be an Eastern Conference All-Star starter. She scored six points and added four assists. ... The game was delayed for a few seconds in the second half when the ball got stuck between the rim and backboard. ... Feaster had a four-point play with 8:41 to go. ... The Sting hit 12 3s in an overtime game against Los Angeles on June 1, 2002.
